I have the K♠ 4♠, giving me a King-high flush (all five cards on the board are spades, and my K♠ is the highest). There are no full houses or quads possible (board offers no paired cards), and the highest possible straight (10-J-Q-K-A) utilizes the A♣ which is not a spade, so no higher flush containing the Q♠ or straight-flush is possible.

Thus I hold the effective nuts.

With a 120-chip pot and 940 effective behind, I want to get paid.

[Raise 120]

Turn evaluation:
- Board double-paired (2♠-6♦-6♠-4♠) – paired sixes devalue our A-high.
- Outs: only three aces give us top pair/two-pair; any further bet is largely a bluff because we rarely improve.
- Effective stack depth: P0 has 800 (we cover), so folding away our equity for free is too weak. However, betting for value is thin – worse hands will fold and better will call or raise.
- Optimum line: take a small stab to pick up the pot when he holds a pocket below sixes, some random 2-x, total air, etc.; small sizing keeps our range balanced and inexpensive when behind.

[Call]

rounds.response:
I’m the Big Blind this hand, holding A♦ 5♣ on the river with the board reading 2♣ 6♦ 6♠ 4♠ A♥.  I have two-pair aces and sixes with an ace kicker.  My only live opponent checked behind on the turn and has checked to me; there is a 40-chip pot and zero further action required to check through and show down.

Against a single opponent who checked twice (indicative of modest strength), I want to thin-value or check.  However, this board texture hits a lot of his likely ranges: any pocket pair, any ace, or even something like 65/54 or 32.  Given only 40 in the pot, value here is thin.  Betting will rarely fold out a better hand (he has 800 chips behind which easily covers a bet), and I am never getting called by worse and folding out better.

For these reasons, checking is the higher EV play.

[Check]
